'''Charles DeWitt Watts''' (September 21, 1917 <U+2013> July 12, 2004) was an [[African American]] [[surgeon]] and [[Activism|activist]] for the poor. Watts was the first surgeon of African American ancestry in [[North Carolina]]. Earning his medical degree in 1943 from [[Howard University|Howard University College]], he was the first African American board certified surgeon to serve in North Carolina. After surgical training at Freedman's Hospital in [[Washington, D.C.]] in 1949, he moved to [[Durham, North Carolina]] in 1950 and established a clinic to provide access to medical services for the poor. Breaking the social customs of racial obstacles, he advocated for certification of African American medical students. He also became a member of many professional colleges including the [[National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Science's Institute of Medicine]] and the [[American College of Surgeons]].<ref name=3Watt>{{cite web|title=Obituary for Charles DeWitt Watts, M.D.|url=http://corporate.dukemedicine.org/news_and_publications/news_office/news/7979|website=http://corporate.dukemedicine.org|publisher=Duke Medicine News and Communications|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.co.in/books?id=R6FLAAAAYAAJ&q=Dr.+Charles+DeWitt+Watts&dq=Dr.+Charles+DeWitt+Watts|title=Journal of the National Medical Association Contributor National Medical Association (U.S.)|publisher= Appleton -Century -Crofts|date=28 January 2010|origyear=1975|via= Cornell University}}</ref> He served as chief of surgery at Durham's Lincoln Hospital and was later one of the key figures in converting it to the [[Lincoln Community Health Center]], a low-priced clinic for the poor.

== Early life and education ==
Charles DeWitt Watts was born on September{{nbsp}}21, 1917, to parents who were church members in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref name=3Watt /> He was the youngest of four children.  His father owned a country store consisting of a butcher shop and a fruit store. The parents taught their children the importance of hard work. Watt's daughter, Constance Eileen Watts Welch, later said "It was his work with the butcher that taught him the anatomy of animals before formally studying it, when he made steaks and roasts<U+2026>". Since his father had six sisters who desired to attend college, his father was not able to complete his studies in college; however, he urged his children to attain "academic excellence without excuse".<ref name=6Watt>{{cite web|title=Dr. Watts epitomized a man of character, vision, perseverance and activism|url=http://www.sepk20.com/lincolncommhealth622.html|website=http://www.sepk20.com|publisher=sepk20.com|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref>

Watts was selected to attend Atlanta University Laboratory High School, a school created for exceptional students who were college bound, located at [[Spelman College]]'s campus.<ref name=8Watt>{{cite web|title=First black N.C. surgeon dies at 86|url=http://www.accessnorthga.com/detail-pf.php?n=164935|website=http://www.accessnorthga.com|publisher=Access North|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref> He then enrolled at [[Morehouse College]] where during his first year his father died.<ref name=6Watt /> At that time, he and his brother worked a paper route, delivering copies of the ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|Atlanta Constitution]]'' every morning to support their education.<ref name=6Watt /><ref name=8Watt /> Watts was encouraged to attend medical school by his Morehouse College biology teacher, Samuel Nabrit, as he was good at science subjects, especially biology. Watts received a degree in mathematics in 1938 from Morehouse College. After working at the Washington, D.C., post office to support his education, Watts attended [[Howard University College of Medicine]].<ref name=6Watt />

== Career ==
Watts received his medical degree in 1943 from Howard University College of Medicine and become the first African American in North Carolina to become a board certified surgeon.<ref name=8Watt /><ref name=1Watt>{{cite web|title=Dr. Charles Watts gave help to the poor|url=http://www.aaregistry.org/historic_events/view/dr-charles-watts-gave-help-poor|website=http://www.aaregistry.org|publisher=African American Registry|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=2Watt>{{cite web|author1=Yvonne Shinhoster Lamb|title=Charles DeWitt Watts, 86; Surgeon, Howard Trustee|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A61543-2004Aug12.html|website=http://www.washingtonpost.com|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=17 December 2014|page=B06|date=13 August 2004}}</ref><ref name=4Watt>{{cite web|title=Dr. Charles DeWitt Watts (1917<U+2013>2004) Mentor and Champion of Desegregated Hospitals|url=http://www.graphic-leespeaking.com/black_history_tribute/id122.html|website=http://www.graphic-leespeaking.com|publisher=graphic-leespeaking.com|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref> After graduation, he moved to [[Washington, D.C.]] and completed surgical training at [[Freedmen's Hospital|Freedman's Hospital]] in 1949, under the tutorship of [[Charles R. Drew]].<ref name=3Watt /><ref name=11Watt /> Drew was credited by Watts for inspiring and encouraging him in his surgical career.<ref name=6Watt /> Drew was a pioneer of his time for his research on blood and plasma.<ref name=2Watt /><ref>{{cite book|title=The Crisis|date=October 2004|publisher=The Crisis Publishing Company|page=13|edition=5|chapter=111|issn=0011-1422|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=6EIEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA13}}</ref> According to Watts's daughter, "It was because of Dr. Drew's encouragement that he went back to Howard... and went through the surgery training program".<ref name=2Watt /> Watts noted in an interview with ''[[The Washington Post]]'' in 1986 that "He [Charles Drew] wanted black doctors to go out and establish themselves around the country".<ref name=2Watt />
[[File:LincolnHosp.jpg|thumb|right|The original Lincoln Hospital, at the northwest corner of Proctor and Cozart streets, circa 1901]]
Between 1948 and 1950, he worked as a surgery instructor at Howard University.<ref name=1Watt /><ref name=2Watt /><ref name=4Watt />

In 1950, Watts settled in Durham, N.C. with his wife, Constance Merrick Watts, a native of the town.<ref name=1Watt /> He opened a private clinic in general surgery for poor people and African Americans, as blacks had very limited access to medical services.<ref name=1Watt /><ref name=2Watt /> In 1965, he was the chief of surgery at the Lincoln Hospital, which was one of the city's few hospitals to serve blacks.<ref name=8Watt /><ref name=2Watt /><ref name=4Watt /> The hospital consisted of 150 beds.<ref name=6Watt /> The hospital was also one of the few hospitals in America at that time which allow African American doctors to perform surgery.<ref name=1Watt /> While working as chief of surgery Watts also served as a trainer for the hospital's interns.<ref name=1Watt /><ref name=2Watt /> In the 1970s he played a major role in establishing the [[Lincoln Community Health Center]].

In 1975, Watts retired from performing surgery. His daughter said, "I also think he was worried about his dexterity and eyesight".<ref name=4Watt />
[[File:LCHC.png|thumb|right|300px|The front entrance of [[Lincoln Community Health Center]]]] He later become a clinical professor of surgery and director of student health at [[Duke University School of Medicine|Duke University Medical School]] and [[North Carolina Central University]] respectively. He also served as a vice president and medical director for 28 years at the [[North Carolina Mutual Life Insurance Company]], an insurance company founded by the grandfathers of Constance Merrick Watts.<ref name=8Watt /><ref name=11Watt>{{cite web|title=Dr. Charles DeWitt Watts (1917<U+2013>2004)|url=http://guides.mclibrary.duke.edu/content_mobile.php?pid=553146&sid=4559707|website=http://guides.mclibrary.duke.edu|publisher=Duke.edu|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref>

He worked throughout his life to serve medical facilities for the poor and help the black communities, breaking the social custom of racial discrimination when he advocated for the certification of black medical students.<ref name=3Watt /><ref name=2Watt /><ref name=10Watt>{{cite web|title=Charles DeWitt Watts Advocating for civil and human rights|url=http://www.blackdoctorscolumbusohio.com/black_medical_history.htm|website=http://www.blackdoctorscolumbusohio.com|publisher=blackdoctorscolumbusohio.com via Duke University Medical Center Library|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref>
One of his former students, Charles Johnson, noted that "He [Watts] clearly was a visionary" and added that "He was a very bright, energetic, capable physician and always (was interested in) helping the black community to whatever extent he could".<ref name=8Watt />

He served as a member of Howard's Board of Trustees for 19 years, retiring in 1993.<ref name=4Watt />

== Personal life ==
Watts married Constance Merrick Watts in 1945. She was a graduate with a major in economics from [[Spelman College]] and a community volunteer. A native of Durham, she attended [[Palmer Memorial Institute]].<ref name=6Watt /> Constance Eileen Watts, later Constance Eileen Watts Welch, was their first child, born March{{nbsp}}28, 1946 at Lincoln Hospital.<ref name=6Watt /><ref name=9Watt>{{cite web|title=Constance Eileen Watts Welch, daughter of Charles Watts|url=http://www.thehistorymakers.com/biography/c-eileen-watts-welch-41|website=http://www.thehistorymakers.com|publisher=The History Makers|accessdate=17 December 2014|date=23 June 2007}}</ref> They later had three more children: two daughters,  Deborah Chase Watts Hill and Winifred A. Watts Hemphill and a son, Charles D. Watts, Jr.<ref name=3Watt /> After attending [[Hillside High School (Durham, North Carolina)|Hillside High School]], Durham, and earning a B. A. degree from Spelman College, Atlanta, Eileen Watts Welch became an academic administrator.<ref name=9Watt /><ref name=5Watt>{{cite web|title=Biography of Eileen Watts|url=http://blog.oup.com/2011/06/eileen-watts-welch/|website=http://blog.oup.com|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] (Blog)|accessdate=17 December 2014|date=June 2011}}</ref> Charles DeWitt Watts, Jr. ("Chuck"), graduated from the [[University of North Carolina]] in 1977, earned MBA and law degrees, and became a law professor, practicing attorney, and community leader.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://alumni.unc.edu/article.aspx?sid=9560|title=Harvey E. Beech Award: Charles Dewitt Watts, Jr. '77|work=UNC General Alumni Association|accessdate=18 December 2014}}</ref> In 1992, Deborah Watts Hill died of breast cancer.<ref name=1Watt /><ref name=4Watt />

== Death ==
After a career of more than 50 years,<ref name=10Watt /> Watts died at home aged 86 on July{{nbsp}}12, 2004 due to complications from diabetes and heart disease.<ref name=1Watt /><ref name=2Watt /><ref name=4Watt /><ref>{{cite web|title=North Carolia's First African American Surgeon|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?GRid=9095217&page=gr|website=http://www.findagrave.com|publisher=Find A Grave|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref> After a funeral at St. Joseph<U+2019>s AME Church, Fayetteville Street, Durham, he was interred at [[Beechwood Cemetery]], Fayetteville Street, Durham.<ref name=3Watt /><ref name=8Watt /> William Anlyan, former chancellor of Duke University Medical Center for Health affairs, said on hearing of Watts's death, "We grew to be great friends [Watts and Anlyan]. He was a well-trained and gentle surgeon, and he and his family became great assets to entire Durham community".<ref name=3Watt />

== Recognition ==
In 2002, Duke Medical School started a scholarship in his name, the Charles Watts Travel Awards, to "assist student and faculty travel to study culturally specific issues."<ref name=3Watt /> Duke also awarded him an honorary degree.<ref name =3Watt />

His collected papers are archived at the Duke University Libraries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/findingaids/wattscharlesdewitt/|title=Guide to the Charles DeWitt Watts Papers, 1917<U+2013>2004 and undated|work=Duke University Libraries|accessdate=18 December 2014}}</ref>

